      "title": "Start with a simple 50/30/20 rule",
      "readingTime": "5 min",
      "tags": ["budget", "basics"],
      "body": "The 50/30/20 rule is a simple way to see where your money should go each month. The idea is: 50% for needs (rent, groceries, utilities), 30% for wants (eating out, subscriptions, hobbies), and 20% for savings and debt goals.\n\nStep 1: Calculate your monthly take-home income (money that arrives to your account after taxes). If your income changes, use an average from the last 3 months.\n\nStep 2: List your needs. A “need” is something you must pay to keep your life stable: housing, basic food, transport to work, phone/internet, and minimum debt payments.\n\nStep 3: List wants. These are nice-to-have expenses that you can reduce without breaking your life. This category is where most people find quick savings.\n\nStep 4: Put at least something into savings. If 20% is too hard today, start with 5% or 10%. The rule still works because it gives you a target and a structure.\n\nTip: Use the rule as a direction, not a strict law. If your rent is high and needs take 60%, don’t give up. Focus on reducing wants and building a small savings habit first.\n\nGoal: after 2–3 months you should clearly see what to cut, what to keep, and how much you can save without feeling stressed."
