      "id": "save-002",
      "title": "Create an emergency buffer before investing",
      "readingTime": "6 min",
      "tags": ["emergency", "safety", "basics"],
      "body": "Before you invest or take a loan, build an emergency buffer. This is a separate pot of money that protects you from unexpected situations: medical bills, urgent travel, broken phone, job delays, or sudden repair costs.\n\nWhy it matters: without a buffer, every surprise becomes a crisis. People often take expensive loans not because they want to, but because they have no cash when a problem happens.\n\nStep 1: Define your “essential expenses.” Add up rent/mortgage, basic food, utilities, transport, and minimum debt payments.\n\nStep 2: Set the first target: 1 month of essential expenses. If that number is too big, start with a smaller milestone like 200–500 EUR. Early wins matter.\n\nStep 3: Choose where to keep it. Use a separate savings account so you don’t accidentally spend it. Keep it accessible, but not too easy to touch.\n\nStep 4: Automate it (even small). A consistent 20–50 EUR every payday is better than random big deposits.\n\nStep 5: Grow from 1 month to 3 months. Three months gives most people real stability.\n\nRule: Only use this buffer for real emergencies. Not for discounts, not for parties, not for “I deserve it.”\n\nWhen the buffer is ready, you can start saving for goals or investing with less stress and fewer financial mistakes."
