    {
      "id": "save-003",
      "title": "Automate savings on payday",
      "readingTime": "5 min",
      "tags": ["automation", "habits", "basics"],
      "body": "Automation is one of the strongest saving tools because it removes decision-making. If you wait until the end of the month, you usually save what is left. If you automate on payday, you save first.\n\nStep 1: Pick a percentage or a fixed amount. Start small (5–10% or 25–50 EUR). The goal is to make it sustainable.\n\nStep 2: Set an automatic transfer on the day your salary arrives (or the next morning). Move money from your main account to a savings account.\n\nStep 3: Label your savings account. Example: “Emergency Buffer” or “Goals.” Labels help you respect the money.\n\nStep 4: Increase slowly. Every month or every two months, increase the amount by a small step (5–10 EUR). You will barely feel it, but it compounds.\n\nStep 5: Protect the habit. If you get a bonus or extra income, automatically save a part of it too (for example 30%).\n\nCommon mistake: saving too much too fast and then quitting. A smaller automated amount that stays for 12 months beats a big amount that lasts 2 weeks.\n\nResult: automation turns saving into a default behavior, not a fight with yourself."
