      "id": "save-005",
      "title": "Use a weekly money plan instead of a monthly one",
      "readingTime": "6 min",
      "tags": ["budget", "planning", "basics"],
      "body": "Monthly budgets fail because life happens daily, not monthly. A weekly plan gives you faster control and fewer surprises.\n\nStep 1: Take your monthly take-home income and divide by 4.3 (average weeks per month). That’s your weekly spending capacity.\n\nStep 2: Subtract fixed bills that are not weekly (rent, insurance). Put that money aside first.\n\nStep 3: Create a weekly limit for variable spending (food, transport, entertainment).\n\nStep 4: Every week, check your remaining amount. If you overspent, adjust next week. If you underspent, move the extra to savings.\n\nWhy this works: a weekly plan gives you immediate feedback. You don’t wait until the end of the month to realize you have a problem.\n\nTip: If you have irregular income, base your weekly plan on the lowest realistic income month, and treat extra money as bonus for savings.\n\nResult: budgeting becomes simpler because you focus on “this week,” not “this entire month.”"
    },
