      "title": "Use the ‘24-hour rule’ to stop impulse purchases",
      "readingTime": "4 min",
      "tags": ["habits", "shopping", "mindset"],
      "body": "Impulse purchases often happen because the decision is fast. The 24-hour rule slows the decision and gives your brain time to switch from emotion to logic.\n\nHow it works:\n- If you want something non-essential, wait 24 hours before buying.\n- For bigger items, wait 72 hours.\n\nStep 1: When you feel the urge, write the item down (or add to a wishlist).\n\nStep 2: Ask yourself after 24 hours:\n- Do I still want it?\n- Is it worth giving up one week of savings for it?\n- Is there a cheaper alternative?\n\nStep 3: If you still want it, buy it—but do it intentionally.\n\nTip: This method doesn’t ban spending. It turns spending into a choice.\n\nOutcome: most impulse wants disappear, and your savings grow without feeling like a strict diet."
